l-default md"><h2>Intro</h2><p>This is a simple applet showcasing the power=
 of the <a href=3D"https://github.com/MedicalMasses-L-L-C/rumtk">rumtk</a> =
framework. The goal of this applet is to provide a simple interface for run=
ning different kinds of benchmarks on the framework. I also hope to add an =
export feature to the applet so the results can be saved to disk for record=
 keeping.</p><p>This utility is not specific to the <a href=3D"https://gith=
ub.com/MedicalMasses-L-L-C/rumtk">rumtk</a> toolset. You can configure your=
 own profiles to examine your own programs. This benchmarking tool might no=
t be appropriate for interpreted programs since we look at the binary's cal=
l stack. As a result, I suspect that the only useful information you might =
obtain from benchmarking an interpreted program is statistics about the int=
erpreter itself.</p><h3>The benchmark report is broken down into these sect=
ions:</h3><ul><li><code>Meta</code>: A small section showing the target arc=
hitecture and OS of this <code>rumtk-benchmark</code> build.</li><li><code>=
File List</code>: list of test files and their sizes in MB used for running=
 test of utility.</li><li><code>Basic</code>: A simple run of the selected =
utility using <code>hyperfine</code>. The resulting report shows the mean t=
imes with breakdowns by user and kernel spaces.</li><li><code>Flamegraph</c=
ode>: Interactive flamegraph attempting to visualize call graph of the test=
 utility under load. Helpful in identifying function targets of interest fo=
r future optimizations. This visualization is generated by performing a qui=
ck benchmark with the <code>perf</code> command and then passing the report=
 to <a href=3D"https://github.com/flamegraph-rs/flamegraph">flamegraph-rs</=
a>.</li><li><code>CPU Summary</code>: Simple summary report of basic CPU st=
atistics obtained with the <code>perf</code> command.</li><li><code>CPU Cac=
he &amp; Branch Misses</code>: Report of functions showing a % cache and br=
anch miss of &gt; 1%. This helps with identifying if the performance issue =
is coming from a large number of CPU cache misses. Meaning, if the program =
is not maximizing the usage of the data already present in the CPU cache li=
nes or a failure of the program to pre-train the CPU algorithm to prefetch =
necessary data. You do get a technical subreport of the current</li></ul><h=
3>Wishlist:</h3><ul><li><code>Network Summary</code>: Report of the local n=
etwork information.</li><li><code>Network Stress Test</code>: Test the inte=
rfaces against the message and record information about how fast everything=
 moves through the pipes.</li></ul><h3>Information that is not collected:</=
h3><ul><li><code>O Analysis</code>: Currently, we do not gather the informa=
tion necessary to analyze the general behavior of the program or algorithm.=
 Therefore, this benchmark utility does not provide big O notation informat=
ion.</li><li><code>SIMD</code>: Currently, this utility does not inspect an=
d present a dissassembly of the test program and in particular the key func=
tions. Thus, no information about proper usage of <strong>SIMD</strong> ext=
ensions can be ascertain. I recommend you use Matt Goldbolt's excellent <a =
href=3D"https://godbolt.org/">Compiler Explorer</a> tool or <code>objdump</=
code> for that.</li></ul><h2>Contributing</h2><p>If you appreciate the work=
 done in this project, please, visit the following links:</p><ul><li><a hre=
f=3D"https://opencollective.com/medicalmasses-llc">OpenCollective</a>.</li>=
<li>Navigate to <a href=3D"https://medicalmasses.com/">MedicalMasses L.L.C.=
's</a> website.</li><li>Or reach out to <a href=3D"mailto:lsantos@medicalma=
